page.text: Salt Lake Boulevard between Maluna Street and Ala Liliko‘i Street
The City and County of Honolulu (City) is proposing to expand Salt Lake Boulevard between
Maluna Street and Ala Liliko‘i Street from two lanes to four lanes (two eastbound, two
westbound) and include a median, dedicated bike lanes, sidewalk, and on-street parking. This
project would increase the capacity of the boulevard to accommodate existing and projected
traffic volumes through the years ahead. It would complete the final section of the overall Salt
Lake Boulevard widening project from Pu‘uloa Road and Kahuā‘paani Street that initially
started in the late 1970s. Three alternative road widening concepts, plus a “no action”
alternative, were considered for the project. Except for the “no action” alternative, all of the
alternatives include five basic design elements: widening from two travel lanes to four travel
lanes with a median/left-turn storage lane, provision of on-street parking, addition of bike
lanes and improved sidewalks, and installation of stormwater drainage systems. Alternatives
A and B include underground detention basins to retain stormwater; Alternative C includes
The provision of dedicated bike lanes is consistent with the City’s “complete streets” program
to include public street facilities to accommodate all modes of transportation. The addition of
a parking lane within the right-of-way would allow adjacent residents to continue on-street
parking fronting their homes. The median could serve as a left-turn storage lane and allow
eastbound vehicles to turn left into adjacent residential driveways or serve as a spatial buffer
and landscaped feature between the eastbound lanes and the westbound lanes. All
improvements including shoulder improvements and retaining walls would be constructed
within the boulevard’s existing right-of-way, except for some areas that require minor
grading modifications at intersection approaches and drainage system connections, and in
one alternative, retaining walls in the adjacent downslope property, as described in
During construction, short-term temporary impacts are expected to be generated by
construction vehicles, machinery, and tools and equipment involved in site preparation, road
construction, landscaping, and cleanup. Probable impacts would include fugitive dust,
construction noise, erosion and sedimentation, and traffic slowdowns and detours through
Construction of the road improvements is not expected to displace any existing residences or
community facilities. No impacts are anticipated on any archaeological or cultural resources
nor any endangered or threatened flora or fauna species. Depending on the final road
widening design, use of the adjacent Navy land might be necessary. In that case, Navy
authorization would be required and a NEPA environmental review triggered by use of
Federal land as well as Federal funds.
When construction is completed and the widened road is in full operation, potential impacts
would include improved traffic flow through the Salt Lake Boulevard corridor, increased
traffic noise, improved street lighting, safer pathways for bicyclists and pedestrians,
controlled on-street parking, and a visually enhanced roadway environment. The speed limit
is expected to match the completed portions of the overall Salt Lake Boulevard widening
During construction, best management practices (BMPs) would be employed to control
fugitive dust. In compliance with state statutory and regulatory requirements, measures
would be implemented to minimize noise generated from the construction site. For erosion
and sedimentation control, BMPs would be applied as required under National Pollutant
Discharge Elimination System (NPDES) permits. Net increases in storm water runoff would be
A City-approved traffic control plan would be implemented to minimize construction impact
on traffic through the project corridor. Should use of any Navy land be required for the road
widening, approval from the proper federal authorities would be first obtained.

This environmental assessment (EA) is being prepared for the final phase of the City and
County of Honolulu’s (City) Salt Lake Boulevard Widening Project (see Figure 1-1). Since City
action and land are involved, a Chapter 343, Hawai‘i Revised Statutes (HRS), environmental
document is being prepared. Further, as Federal-aid highway funding would be sought for the
project’s implementation, this EA is designed to be in compliance with the National
Environmental Policy Act (NEPA) (42 United States Code [USC] § 4321, et seq.) as
administered by the national Council on Environmental Quality (CEQ).
The Environmental Impact Statement (EIS) for the original Salt Lake Boulevard Widening
Project, from Pu‘uloa Road to Kahuapā‘ani Street, was approved by the FHWA on February 4,
1977. Since that date, construction on the project occurred in phases starting with Increment
1, Phases 1 and 2, which extended from Pu‘uloa Road to Ala Liliko‘i Street. Construction of
that section was completed in the early 1980s. Construction of Increment 2, Phases 1 and 2,
which extended from Kahuapā‘ani Street to Maluna Street, was completed in 2005.

community changed and new environmental review requirements evolved, requiring a re-

EA for Increment 2, Phase 2, and a notice of its availability was published in the Office of
Environmental Quality Control’s (OEQC) The Environmental Notice. Since that publication,
revisions were made to the design of the Phase 2 road section, and a revised EA was prepared
and announced in the OEQC bulletin in 2001.

The full length of Salt Lake Boulevard is a collector road for traffic generated in the Salt Lake,
Foster Village, Hālawa, Makalapa, and Navy housing communities located inland or north of
the Honolulu International Airport. This boulevard also serves as a connector right-of-way for
the adjacent neighborhoods, including Māpunapuna, Āliamanu, Moanalua, and Aloha Stadium
The purpose and need for the original 2.8-mile Salt Lake Boulevard Widening Project,
between Pu‘uloa Road and Kahuapā‘ani Street, stated:
“The project is needed because the present facility is inadequate to serve the
growing needs of the surrounding communities. With the ultimate
development of the surrounding area, traffic conditions will become
intolerable. The City and County elects to improve the existing roadway
because of this necessity, its central location, existing wide right-of-way of
100-feet width which has been set aside for roadway purposes, and because
other alignments or alternatives are either impractical or will cause much
greater environmental impact on the surrounding communities.”
In years prior to the 1977 Salt Lake Boulevard Widening Project EIS, development of nearby
residential subdivisions, schools, shopping centers, churches, and recreational facilities
generated increases in traffic volumes and a need to expand the then existing two-lane Salt
Lake Boulevard to multiple lanes. In later years, results from a 1996 updated traffic study
confirmed the need to widen Salt Lake Boulevard as described in the 1977 EIS.
A 2012 traffic study was conducted for this EA (see Appendix B) to update the traffic study
completed in 1996. This study reconfirmed the occurrence of congestion along Salt Lake
Boulevard particularly at the intersections in Phase 3 (see Table 1-1). The study estimated
that traffic volumes would continue to increase at a rate of 1.27 percent per year, and that
current congestion would worsen if no improvements are made between Maluna Street and
Ala Liliko‘i Street. Projections in the 2012 Highway Capacity Manual study show that the
signalized intersections at Salt Lake Boulevard and Wanaka Street and Salt Lake Boulevard

Policy 4 of this objective states: “Improve roads in existing communities to reduce congestion
and eliminate unsafe conditions.” This objective and policy of the City identify the need to
improve transportation facilities for its residents to include adequate road systems for
vehicles and for other modes of transportation for all residents.
The Primary Urban Center (PUC) Development Plan, which was adopted in 2004 to
implement the policies of the General Plan, focuses on transportation policies to develop a
The plan recognizes the need to increase
roadway capacity to accommodate the high rate of growth in automobile traffic within the
PUC. It notes that acquisition of right-of-ways to build new or to widen existing thoroughfares
is severely constrained by high costs and limited space. For the Salt Lake Boulevard project, a
100-foot wide right-of-way already exists to accommodate the planned improvements.
To foster the development of a balanced transportation system, key objectives in the PUC
Development Plan are to support transit and coordinate land use policies and regulations
with transit development, generate interest and amenities for pedestrians along travel routes,
manage transportation demand, and improve bicycling facilities. From these adopted public
plans, the intent to accommodate multimodal travel along Salt Lake Boulevard and the need
to install adequate pedestrian sidewalks and bicycle ways are evident.
The PUC Development Plan further states that O‘ahu’s official long-range surface
transportation strategy is documented in the O‘ahu Regional Transportation Plan, a federally
mandated document that is updated every five years by the O‘ahu Metropolitan Planning
Organization (OMPO). The most recent update, entitled O‘ahu Regional Transportation Plan
2035, was approved by the OMPO Policy Committee in April 2011. That plan identifies
priority projects for its mid-range timeframe and long-range timeframe based on project
needs and anticipated funding. Salt Lake Boulevard Widening between Maluna Street and Ala
Liliko‘i has been delegated Project No. 31 and listed under the Plan’s mid-range projects.
Implementation of the mid-range projects is anticipated between 2011 and 2020.

of Transportation (DOT) and Hawai‘i’s four county transportation departments to adopt
“complete streets” policies. The intent is to accommodate all users of roadways, including

The City is proposing to widen Salt Lake Boulevard from two lanes to four lanes to reduce
traffic congestion and delays and to accommodate the anticipated increase in traffic volumes
over the coming years. Planning and traffic studies were conducted to determine the design
requirements for the road improvements. Additional roadway elements such as parking
lanes, bike lanes, sidewalks, and bioswales were included to comply with City General Plan,
Development Plan, Complete Streets, and Low Impact Development (LID) policies. The year
2040 was selected as the planning horizon due to funding requirements which requires the
project year to be 20 years from the anticipated completion year of the project. Depending on
available project funding, the anticipated start of construction is as early as 2018. The
duration of construction could be two years or, if phasing is necessary, somewhat longer.
For the Phase 3 section of the Salt Lake Boulevard Widening Project, the City is proposing to
add two new travel lanes (one in each direction), on-street parking, a median, bike lanes,
pedestrian sidewalk, landscaping, and drainage improvements to the existing right-of-way to
meet the project’s purpose and need. Provision of the new roadway elements triggers a
number of variations and options, each with different costs and benefits as well as different
environmental impacts. In the remainder of this chapter, the EA will identify four proposed
action alternatives comprised of a combination of different roadway elements that work well
together. For the proposing agency, a preferred alternative may be selected at the end of the
Draft EA review or a selection of roadway elements from the various alternatives may be
combined to comprise the desired proposed action alternative. Chapters 3 and 4 of this
document will present the evaluation of the four alternatives in terms of their impacts on the
